07676nam a22010695i 9780812206173DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979754113  a97808122061737 a10.9783/97808122061732doi  a(DE-B1597)449520  a(OCoLC)822017943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD9502.A2bB49 2012 7aPOL0240002bisacsh04a333.700aBeyond the Resource Curse /ced. by Taleh Ziyadov, Brenda Shaffer. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (512 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Economics and Infrastructures of Energy Exporters -- t1. The Natural Resource Curse: A Survey -- t2. Sometimes the Grass Is Indeed Greener: The Successful Use of Energy Revenues -- t3. Is There a Policy Learning Curve? Trinidad and Tobago and the 2004– 8 Hydrocarbon Boom -- t4. The Illusion of Unlimited Supply: Iran and Energy Subsidies -- t5. Challenges Facing Central Banks in Oil- Exporting Countries: The Case of Azerbaijan -- t6. Power to the Producers: The Challenges of Electricity Provision in Major Energy- Exporting States -- tPart II: Energy Exports, Society, and Politics -- t7. The Impact of Energy Resources on Nation- and State- Building: The Contrasting Cases of Azerbaijan and Georgia -- t8. Education Reform in Energy- Exporting States: The Post- Soviet Experience in Comparative Perspective -- t9. Is Norway Really Norway? -- tPart III: Energy Exporters in the International Po liti cal System -- t10. Energy Exporters and the International Energy Agency -- t11. Resource Nationalism and Oil Development: Profit or Peril? -- t12. Natural Resources, Domestic Instability, and International Conflicts -- t13. Petroleum, Governance, and Fragility: The Micro- Politics of Petroleum in Postconflict States -- tConclusion: Constant Perils, Policy Responses, and Lessons to Be Learned -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen countries discover that they possess large deposits of oil and natural gas, the news is usually welcome. Yet, paradoxically, if they rely on their wealth of natural resources, they often set down a path of poor economic performance and governance challenges. Only a few resource-rich countries have managed to develop their economies fully and provide a better and sustainable standard of living for large segments of their populations. This phenomenon, known as the resource curse, is a core challenge for energy-exporting states. Beyond the Resource Curse focuses on this relationship between natural wealth and economic security, discussing the particular pitfalls and consistent perils facing oil- and gas-exporting states.The contributors to this volume look beyond the standard fields of research related to the resource curse. They also shed new light on the specific developmental problems of resource-rich exporting states around the globe, including Azerbaijan, Bahrain, Cambodia, East Timor, Iran, Norway, Russia, Trinidad and Tobago, the United Arab Emirates, and Venezuela.Policy makers and academics think of energy security solely in terms of the interests of energy importers. Beyond the Resource Curse shows that the constant volatility in energy markets creates energy security challenges for exporters as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnergy policy. 0aInternational relations. 0aNatural gas reserves. 0aPetroleum reserves. 0aPower resources. 0aResource curse. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh  aBusiness.  aEconomics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Pol